"# Chapter 12 — 16 voices and the voice-16 mixer

Composer v1.1 introduced a 16-voice polyphony bank with voice 16 dedicated as a mixer. This chapter walks the voice-pool widget, how voice-steal works, and how the mixer composes voices 1-15 into a single output stream.

## 12.1 Why 16

PICO-8 has 4 voices. TIC-80 has 4 voices. Both hit the ceiling when a kid writes a beat with kick, snare, bass, and a two-note chord — the fifth voice cuts one of the earlier voices. The kid's music sounds broken and the tool has no message that explains it.

Modern devices, even Chromebooks, run 16 concurrent oscillators comfortably. Composer v1.1 raises the ceiling to 16 and dedicates voice 16 as a mixer for when you want to route several voices into a shared processing chain.

## 12.2 The voice-pool widget

```
(composer/voice-pool :bind :steal . options)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the pool state writes.
- `:steal` — symbol, optional. Voice-steal policy. Default `'oldest`.

Verified:

```scheme
(composer/voice-pool :bind '(cart :pool) :steal 'oldest)
```

Returns a voice-pool record with 16 voice slots. Slots 1-15 are individual voice slots; slot 16 is the mixer.

## 12.3 The song/config verb

```
(song/config :voices N :voice-steal POLICY :bpm BPM)
```

Creates a song-config record that tells the runtime how many voices to allocate and what policy to use.

Verified:

```scheme
(song/config :voices 16 :bpm 120)
```

Returns a song-config record with 16 voices at 120 bpm. Voices greater than 16 are clamped to 16 with a warning in the record's `:warnings` field. Voices less than 1 are clamped to 1.

## 12.4 Voice-steal policy

When all voices are busy and a new note wants to play, one existing voice has to yield. The steal policy decides which. v1.1 documents:

- `'oldest` — the voice that has been playing longest. Default.
- `'quietest` — the voice with the lowest current velocity. (Runtime-dependent; the spec proposes it.)
- `'newest` — the most recently triggered voice yields. Unusual; kept as an option.

The steal policy is stored in the pool's options and appears in the emit.

## 12.5 The voice/mix verb

```
(voice/mix voice-ids gain)
```

Creates a mix record that references a list of voice IDs and an optional gain. Verified:

```scheme
(voice/mix '(1 2 3))
```

Returns a `voice-mix` record with voices [1, 2, 3] and gain 1.0. Pass a gain:

```scheme
(voice/mix '(1 2 3) 0.75)
```

Gain is applied to the combined signal.

## 12.6 voice/compose is an alias

`(voice/compose voice-ids gain)` is the same as `(voice/mix voice-ids gain)`. The alias exists per Alfred's phrasing — 'compose them together'. Both verbs produce the same record.

## 12.7 The mixer voice (voice 16)

Voice 16 is not a normal voice. Instead of holding an instrument spec, it holds a `mixes` list — the IDs of the voices it combines. Set the mix with:

```
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3))
```

The pool's voice 16 now takes voices 1, 2, and 3 as inputs.

The mixer is a routing statement. Individual voices still emit their own signals independently; the mixer taps their outputs and combines them.

## 12.8 ASCII mockup — the voice pool

```
voice-pool: 16 voices, steal=oldest
   1 lead
   2 bass
   3 hihat
   4 kick
   5 snare
   6 (free)
   7 (free)
   8 (free)
   9 (free)
  10 (free)
  11 (free)
  12 (free)
  13 (free)
  14 (free)
  15 (free)
  16 [MIX] <- #1,#2
```

Fifteen instrument slots + one mixer routing voices 1 and 2.

## 12.9 Assigning voices

`composer/voice-assign` sets an instrument on a specific voice slot:

```
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument lead))
```

Voice 1 now plays with the `lead` instrument. Voices 2-15 can be assigned independently. Voice 16 refuses instrument assignments (it is the mixer).

## 12.10 The emit shape

The voice-pool emits as:

```
(composer/voice-pool :bind (quote (cart :pool))
                     :steal (quote oldest)
                     :mix (quote (1 2)))
```

Bind path, steal policy, and the current mix list on voice 16. The individual instrument assignments on voices 1-15 live in the target form the widget writes to (analogous to how the piano-roll's note list lives separately from the widget declaration).

## 12.11 A worked example — a 5-voice drum + lead cart

```scheme
(define pool
  (composer/voice-pool :bind '(song :pool) :steal 'oldest))

(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument snare))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument hihat))
(composer/voice-assign pool 4 '(:instrument bass))
(composer/voice-assign pool 5 '(:instrument lead))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3))  ;; drums go to the mixer
```

Five instruments in five voices; voices 1-3 (kick, snare, hihat) are routed to the mixer for shared processing. Voice 4 (bass) and voice 5 (lead) play out directly.

The mixer voice can then have its own fx-chain applied — reverb over the drums, or a shared compressor. The individual voices bypass the mixer.

## 12.12 Why route drums through a mixer

Musicians often want a single reverb applied to the whole drum bus but not to the lead or bass. Routing drums through the mixer gives you that: one reverb on the mixer's output, and the other voices don't touch it.

The composition of voices is data; the routing is data. All in the same file.

## 12.13 What to remember from this chapter

- Composer v1.1 raises polyphony from prior fantasy-console 4 voices to 16.
- The voice-pool widget models 16 voice slots. Slots 1-15 hold individual instruments; slot 16 is a mixer.
- `song/config :voices N` sets voice count (clamped to 1-16). Voices greater than 16 clamp with a warning.
- `voice/mix` and `voice/compose` (the alias) build mix records referencing voice IDs.
- The mixer routes several voices into one output stream for shared processing.
- Voice-steal policy (`'oldest` default) decides which voice yields when the pool is full.
- The pool's emit captures bind path, steal policy, and mixer routing.

Chapter 13 covers save and load — the .slat cart file format in detail.
")
